posts.raw_content:
One guy is over in the computer section just talking on his cellphone at a normal volume or louder. No signs of ending the conversation. Nothing that seems urgent to talk about.

The other guy is nearer to me on the couches using his phone. Texting I guess. Every notification beeps and pings at the maximum volume, and he is playing video shorts from some social media site.

Here's what we all understand about this situation everyday. This isn't a "cultural" because they are Americans like me. This is their conditioned intimidation mindset that they justify "acting out" due to a perceived  victimhood. I think they thrive off the anticipated negative attention they might get because they know they are protected in an isolated public mentality around them. Even the librarians won't dare ask them to stop most likely.

I have EDM going in my earbuds.. but I can still see and hear the comfort level of the people around me. And of course, what is also culturally understood is that if someone says anything to them or asks them to be quiet, there is a 0.01% chance they will say "I'm so sorry, I didn't realize"... instead we all know what will happen. 

We have seen black guys standing on the seats at airport gates with their pants around their thighs because they think "they are ballers". On trains and subways blaring music from their phones because they think "they are rappers". Their public nuisance is intentionally as loud and obnoxious as possible. (It's going to get worse I think too)

Of course, not all black men do this. We all get that too.

But enough to make everyone avoid being around them, living near them, standing near them, trusting them, etc. Until someone changes this or breaks this silent mentality in a large bold public way that goes mainstream, nothing will change. Our peace won't change, and their trapped lifestyle won't change. Of course, yes I could be the one right now to say something but I'm choosing my battles. But I'm quickly advancing to to being completely fine with being called a racist, and I think that is a mutual "cultural" mindset of others too.
